  ('Carioca Build-Up', 'carioca-build-up', 'Perform Carioca Build-Up over a short, clearly marked distance. The athlete rotates or reorients the hips and trunk, moves with intent, brakes or finishes under control, and resets before fatigue changes mechanics.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 2, 5, 20, 30, 50, 'Carioca Build-Up is a Movement Intelligence exercise for rotational footwork rhythm at increasing speed. Use it when the goal is rotational skill, force transfer, or power quality rather than fatigue chasing.', 'Primary subrole: locomotion_sprint_mechanics. Coach Carioca Build-Up as rotational-athlete work: rotation should be organized through feet, hips, pelvis, thoracic spine, shoulders, and the implement or direction change - not forced through the low back.', 'Open the range, feel the turn, and do not force your low back.', 'Rotational running rhythm', 'movement_intelligence', 'locomotion_sprint_mechanics', 'carioca_build_up', '{"primary_joint_actions":["gait or acceleration mechanics","hip rotation","thoracic rotation","trunk bracing"],"primary_tissues":["ankle","core","hip","spine"],"breathing_demand":"low_to_moderate","balance_demand":"moderate_to_high","coordination_demand":"high","impact_level":1,"rotational_power_profile":{"rotation_source":"feet, hips, pelvis, thoracic spine, and shoulders; avoid forced lumbar twisting","sequence_priority":"load or gather, brace, rotate, transfer, finish, and reset","quality_rule":"The rep counts only if the athlete keeps foot pressure, rib-pelvis organization, clean rotational path, safe finish, and a reset that could be repeated."}}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Perform Carioca Build-Up over a short, clearly marked distance. The athlete rotates or reorients the hips and trunk, moves with intent, brakes or finishes under control, and resets before fatigue changes mechanics.","setup":["Clear the training area and define the athlete''s start position, finish position, and stop command.","Mark the lane, cut angle, or finish target with cones so speed and distance are constrained.","Coach one clean practice rep before adding load, speed, partner input, or decision demand."],"execution_steps":["Move into the starting position slowly and find the target joint or stance position.","Rotate, reach, shift, or step through pain-free range while breathing naturally.","Return with control and repeat only as long as the motion improves readiness without fatigue."],"coach_cues":["Rotate from the ground up.","Ribs and pelvis travel as a team.","Own the finish before the next rep.","Open range without forcing it.","Smooth first, then crisp."],"common_faults":["Low back becomes the main rotation point.","Feet lose pressure or the athlete spins on the toes without a controlled base.","Ribs flare, shoulders shrug, or pelvis dumps forward during the turn."],"breathing_cues":["Exhale through effort or release.","Do not hold breath to force rotation.","Recover breathing before the next high-intent rep."],"quality_gate":"The rep counts only if the athlete keeps foot pressure, rib-pelvis organization, clean rotational path, safe finish, and a reset that could be repeated.","stop_signs":["Sharp pain, joint pinch, numbness, tingling, dizziness, or symptom increase.","Lumbar spine becomes the main source of rotation instead of hips, pelvis, thoracic spine, and shoulders.","The athlete loses foot pressure, trunk stack, safe landing, throw accuracy, or controlled reset."]}'::jsonb),
  ('Crossover Run Drill', 'crossover-run-drill', 'Perform Crossover Run Drill over a short, clearly marked distance. The athlete rotates or reorients the hips and trunk, moves with intent, brakes or finishes under control, and resets before fatigue changes mechanics.', 'BEGINNER', 8, 2, 5, 20, 30, 50, 'Crossover Run Drill is a Movement Intelligence exercise for crossover step timing and hip turn. Use it when the goal is rotational skill, force transfer, or power quality rather than fatigue chasing.', 'Primary subrole: locomotion_sprint_mechanics. Coach Crossover Run Drill as rotational-athlete work: rotation should be organized through feet, hips, pelvis, thoracic spine, shoulders, and the implement or direction change - not forced through the low back.', 'Open the range, feel the turn, and do not force your low back.', 'Crossover acceleration mechanics', 'movement_intelligence', 'locomotion_sprint_mechanics', 'crossover_run_drill', '{"primary_joint_actions":["gait or acceleration mechanics","hip rotation","thoracic rotation","trunk bracing"],"primary_tissues":["ankle","core","hip","knee"],"breathing_demand":"low_to_moderate","balance_demand":"high","coordination_demand":"high","impact_level":1,"rotational_power_profile":{"rotation_source":"feet, hips, pelvis, thoracic spine, and shoulders; avoid forced lumbar twisting","sequence_priority":"load or gather, brace, rotate, transfer, finish, and reset","quality_rule":"The rep counts only if the athlete keeps foot pressure, rib-pelvis organization, clean rotational path, safe finish, and a reset that could be repeated."}}'::jsonb, '{"movement_description":"Perform Crossover Run Drill over a short, clearly marked distance. The athlete rotates or reorients the hips and trunk, moves with intent, brakes or finishes under control, and resets before fatigue changes mechanics.","setup":["Clear the training area and define the athlete''s start position, finish position, and stop command.","Mark the lane, cut angle, or finish ta